  <div id="tab-content-research">
    <div class="proj-card" onclick="toggleAbstract('p1')"><div class="proj-header"><div><h3>Relational Polarization: Value Orientations and Immigration Attitudes in Germany</h3><div class="meta">Research Paper · European Social Survey · Ten Rounds</div><div class="tags"><span class="tag accent">Schwartz Value Theory</span><span class="tag accent">Polarization</span><span class="tag accent">Immigration Attitudes</span><span class="tag accent">ESS Data</span></div></div><span id="p1-arrow" class="proj-arrow">▼</span></div><div class="proj-body" id="p1"><p><strong style="color:var(--primary);" data-key="abstract">Abstract</strong></p><p>This study examines the relational structure of value orientations and their association with attitudes toward immigration in Germany using repeated cross-sectional data from ten rounds of the European Social Survey. Self-transcendence aligns with more positive attitudes toward immigrants, whereas conservation aligns with more negative ones. These patterns become more pronounced during periods of heightened societal contestation (2008, 2014, 2016).</p><p class="kw"><strong data-key="keywords">Keywords:</strong> Polarization; Immigration attitudes; Social values; Schwartz value theory; Simmel's theory of valuation; European Social Survey</p></div></div>
    <div class="proj-card" onclick="toggleAbstract('p2')"><div class="proj-header"><div><h3>The Impacts of Ethnic, Political, and Religious Value Differences on the Conflicts in Afghanistan</h3><div class="meta">Bachelor's Thesis · Selçuk University, Sociology · 2022</div><div class="tags"><span class="tag accent">Integrative Literature Review</span><span class="tag accent">Sociology</span><span class="tag accent">Afghanistan</span><span class="tag accent">Conflict Studies</span></div></div><span id="p2-arrow" class="proj-arrow">▼</span></div><div class="proj-body" id="p2"><p><strong style="color:var(--primary);" data-key="abstract">Abstract</strong></p><p>The purpose of this study is to explore the impacts of ethnic, political, and religious value differences on the conflicts in Afghanistan using an integrative literature review. The lack of cross-cutting ties between ethnic groups' value systems combined with fraternal interest groups leads to violent conflicts.</p><p class="kw"><strong data-key="keywords">Keywords:</strong> Value, Conflict, Cross-cutting ties, Fraternal interest group, Afghanistan</p></div></div>
    <div class="proj-card" onclick="toggleAbstract('p3')"><div class="proj-header"><div><h3>The Impact of Artificial Intelligence (AI) on the Simulation Process: From Jean Baudrillard's Perspective</h3><div class="meta" data-key="coauthored">Co-authored with Ziwer Rasul</div><div class="tags"><span class="tag accent">Baudrillard</span><span class="tag accent">AI & Society</span><span class="tag accent">Simulation Theory</span><span class="tag accent">Hyperreality</span></div></div><span id="p3-arrow" class="proj-arrow">▼</span></div><div class="proj-body" id="p3"><p><strong style="color:var(--primary);" data-key="abstract">Abstract</strong></p><p>This study explores the impact of AI on the simulation process through Jean Baudrillard's theory. The findings reveal that AI marks a new phase in the evolution of simulation, transforming our consumer, political, and cultural behaviors.</p><p class="kw"><strong data-key="keywords">Keywords:</strong> Artificial Intelligence, Simulacra, Simulation, Hyperreality, Consumption</p></div></div>
    <div class="proj-card" onclick="toggleAbstract('p4')"><div class="proj-header"><div><h3>The Role of Immigrants' Social Value Orientations in Their Cultural Adaptation Process: A Phenomenology Study in Germany</h3><div class="meta">Research Proposal · Georg-August-Universität Göttingen · Erasmus+ · 2023</div><div class="tags"><span class="tag accent">Phenomenology</span><span class="tag accent">Migration Studies</span><span class="tag accent">MAXQDA</span><span class="tag accent">Qualitative Research</span></div></div><span id="p4-arrow" class="proj-arrow">▼</span></div><div class="proj-body" id="p4"><p><strong style="color:var(--primary);" data-key="abstract">Abstract</strong></p><p>This proposal outlines a qualitative phenomenological study exploring the role of immigrants' social value orientations in their cultural adaptation process. Semi-structured interview questions are based on Schwartz's value scale, Gordon's assimilation formulation, and Berry's acculturation strategies. Data will be collected from approximately 40 immigrants in Germany and analyzed using MAXQDA.</p></div></div>
